","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1254":"1254","of gerrardstown, Meath, Ireland":"Irland","Gerrardstown, County Meath, Ireland":"Gerrardstown, County Meath, Irland","Cushinstown, County Meath, Ireland":"Cushinstown, County Meath, Irland"},"nl":{"1225–":"1225–Overleden","1220–1295":"1220–1295","1238–1299":"1238–1299","1248–1295":"1248–1295","1252–1300":"1252–1300","1254–Male":"1254–Overleden","1225–Female":"1225–Overleden","Abt 1238":"circa 1238","1220":"1220","Abt 1248":"1248","1252":"1252","1295":"1295","abt 1254":"circa 1254","Abt 1252":"circa 1252","1238":"1238","1248":"1248","1225":"1225","1247":"1247","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1254":"1254","of gerrardstown, Meath, Ireland":"Ierland","Gerrardstown, County Meath, Ireland":"Gerrardstown, County Meath, Ierland","Cushinstown, County Meath, Ireland":"Cushinstown, County Meath, Ierland"},"en":{"1225–":"1225–Deceased","1220–1295":"1220–1295","1238–1299":"1238–1299","1248–1295":"1248–1295","1252–1300":"1252–1300","1254–Male":"1254–Deceased","1225–Female":"1225–Deceased","Abt 1238":"about 1238","1220":"1220","Abt 1248":"1248","1252":"1252","1295":"1295","abt 1254":"about 1254","Abt 1252":"about 1252","1238":"1238","1248":"1248","1225":"1225","1247":"1247","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1254":"1254","of gerrardstown, Meath, Ireland":"Ireland","Gerrardstown, County Meath, Ireland":"Gerrardstown, County Meath, Ireland","Cushinstown, County Meath, Ireland":"Cushinstown, County Meath, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Petit","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Alain, Michel, Normand, Mireille, Philippe, Pierre, Achille, Armand, Jean Claude, Jean Jacques, Ketly, Adrien.","French, Walloon, Catalan, English, Jewish (from southern France), West Indian (mainly Haiti), and Mauritian: from (Old) French, Catalan, and Middle English <i>petit</i> ‘small’, hence a nickname for a small man (or an ironic nickname for a big man), or a distinguishing name for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name. Compare   Little  ,   Petee  , and   Petite  .","History: Charles Petit from Anneville-Ambourville in Seine-Maritime, France, married Jeanne Rossignol (Martin and Renée Desjardins) in Quebec City, QC, in 1670. Nicolas Petit <i>dit</i> Lapré/Laprée from Le Gué-d'Alleré in Charente-Maritime, France, married Marie Pouponnel in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1656. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Gobin from Lyon in Rhône married Marguerite Véron in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1692. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Saint-Pierre from Évreux in Eure, France, married Judith Miville in Quebec City, QC, in 1758; see also   St. Pierre  . — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."],"variants":[{"name":"Pattee","meanings":["Altered form of French (Nord) <b>Pety</b>: variant of   Petit  . This surname was brought to North America from England."]},{"name":"Petion","meanings":["French and Haitian (<b>Pétion</b>): diminutive of   Petit  . This surname was brought to the US from Haiti, where it is by far most common."]},{"name":"Petite","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Celestine, Jacques.","French: from the feminine form of   Petit   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Petitt","meanings":["English: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettett","meanings":["English: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Little","meanings":["English: nickname for a small man (if not ironic), or distinguishing epithet for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, from Middle English <i>littel</i>, Old English <i>lȳtel</i> (see   Light   3).","Irish: translation into English of Gaelic <b>Ó Beagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Beagán</i>’ (see   Began  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of any of various European surnames meaning ‘little’, e.g. French   Petit  , Polish <b>Mały</b> (see   Maly   1)."]},{"name":"Petee","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettit","meanings":["English (mainly southeastern): variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Petito","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Carmine, Pasquale, Antonio, Rocco, Alfonzo, Alphonso, Antimo, Emilio, Giovanni, Giuseppe, Orazio, Salvatore, Silvio, Tullio, Virginio.","Italian: nickname for a small man (or an ironic nickname for a tall one), from dialect <i>petito</i> ‘small’ or from the personal name <i>Petito</i>; compare French   Petit  ."]}]},{"name":"Bridget","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of Gaelic Brighid (pronounced ‘breed’); . This was the name of an ancient Celtic goddess, which in Gaulish would have been <i>Brigindos</i>, meaning ‘the exalted one’.  St Brigid  of Kildare (  <i>c.</i>450– <i>c.</i>525 ) is one of the patron saints of Ireland. Very few facts are known about her life. She founded a religious house for women at Kildare, and is said to be have been buried at Downpatrick, where  St Patrick  and  St Columba  were also buried. Many of the stories of miracles told about  St Brigid  seem to be Christianized versions of pagan legends concerning the goddess. The popularity of the name was further reinforced throughout Europe, especially in Scandinavia in the form  <b>Birgit</b> , as the name of the patron saint of Sweden (  1304–73 ). She was a noblewoman of Irish stock who, after the death of her husband, founded an order of nuns, the Bridgettines. Later she went to Rome and attempted to introduce religious reforms there."],"variants":[{"name":"Bridgid","meanings":["Anglicized form of Gaelic Brighid (pronounced ‘breed’); . This was the name of an ancient Celtic goddess, which in Gaulish would have been <i>Brigindos</i>, meaning ‘the exalted one’.  St Brigid  of Kildare (  <i>c.</i>450– <i>c.</i>525 ) is one of the patron saints of Ireland. Very few facts are known about her life. She founded a religious house for women at Kildare, and is said to be have been buried at Downpatrick, where  St Patrick  and  St Columba  were also buried. Many of the stories of miracles told about  St Brigid  seem to be Christianized versions of pagan legends concerning the goddess. The popularity of the name was further reinforced throughout Europe, especially in Scandinavia in the form  <b>Birgit</b> , as the name of the patron saint of Sweden (  1304–73 ). She was a noblewoman of Irish stock who, after the death of her husband, founded an order of nuns, the Bridgettines. Later she went to Rome and attempted to introduce religious reforms there."]},{"name":"Bridgit","meanings":["Anglicized form of Gaelic Brighid (pronounced ‘breed’); . This was the name of an ancient Celtic goddess, which in Gaulish would have been <i>Brigindos</i>, meaning ‘the exalted one’.  St Brigid  of Kildare (  <i>c.</i>450– <i>c.</i>525 ) is one of the patron saints of Ireland. Very few facts are known about her life. She founded a religious house for women at Kildare, and is said to be have been buried at Downpatrick, where  St Patrick  and  St Columba  were also buried. Many of the stories of miracles told about  St Brigid  seem to be Christianized versions of pagan legends concerning the goddess. The popularity of the name was further reinforced throughout Europe, especially in Scandinavia in the form  <b>Birgit</b> , as the name of the patron saint of Sweden (  1304–73 ). She was a noblewoman of Irish stock who, after the death of her husband, founded an order of nuns, the Bridgettines. Later she went to Rome and attempted to introduce religious reforms there."]},{"name":"Brigid","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘the exalted one’.  See  <b>Bridget</b>   ."]},{"name":"Brigit","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘the exalted one’.  See  <b>Bridget</b>   ."]},{"name":"Brighid","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘the exalted one’.  See  <b>Bridget</b>   ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Bridget Petit was born in 1225, in Gerrardstown, County Meath, Ireland. She married Sir Geoffrey de Cusack in 1247, in Gerrardstown, County Meath, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 4 sons."},"et":{"1225–":"1225–Surnud","1220–1295":"1220–1295","1238–1299":"1238–1299","1248–1295":"1248–1295","1252–1300":"1252–1300","1254–Male":"1254–Surnud","1225–Female":"1225–Surnud","Abt 1238":"umbes 1238","1220":"1220","Abt 1248":"1248","1252":"1252","1295":"1295","abt 1254":"umbes 1254","Abt 1252":"umbes 1252","1238":"1238","1248":"1248","1225":"1225","1247":"1247","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1254":"1254","of gerrardstown, Meath, Ireland":"Iirimaa","Gerrardstown, County Meath, Ireland":"Gerrardstown, County Meath, Iirimaa","Cushinstown, County Meath, Ireland":"Cushinstown, County Meath, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1225–":"1225–Kuollut","1220–1295":"1220–1295","1238–1299":"1238–1299","1248–1295":"1248–1295","1252–1300":"1252–1300","1254–Male":"1254–Kuollut","1225–Female":"1225–Kuollut","Abt 1238":"noin 1238","1220":"1220","Abt 1248":"1248","1252":"1252","1295":"1295","abt 1254":"noin 1254","Abt 1252":"noin 1252","1238":"1238","1248":"1248","1225":"1225","1247":"1247","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1254":"1254","of gerrardstown, Meath, Ireland":"Irlanti","Gerrardstown, County Meath, Ireland":"Gerrardstown, County Meath, Irlanti","Cushinstown, County Meath, Ireland":"Cushinstown, County Meath, Irlanti"},"fr":{"1225–":"1225–Décédée","1220–1295":"1220–1295","1238–1299":"1238–1299","1248–1295":"1248–1295","1252–1300":"1252–1300","1254–Male":"1254–Décédé","1225–Female":"1225–Décédée","Abt 1238":"environ 1238","1220":"1220","Abt 1248":"1248","1252":"1252","1295":"1295","abt 1254":"environ 1254","Abt 1252":"environ 1252","1238":"1238","1248":"1248","1225":"1225","1247":"1247","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1254":"1254","of gerrardstown, Me